{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511359"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:41:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:41:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11742"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11742"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.11,0.06,0.02,0.66]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4355"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80579"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4355"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11742"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65870"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"1622"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26958"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80579","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80579"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man is retrieved from the scene of a motor-vehicle crash in which he was an unrestrained front seat passenger. The car crossed the median strip and was involved in a head-on collision. The patient is able to recall the events and he remembers hitting his knee on the dashboard. His only complaint is severe pain in his right hip. His hip is held in flexion and adduction, and he cannot move the leg. He does not have any evidence of any other injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely injury?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fracture of neck of femur","Fracture of the acetabulum","Fracture of the pubic ramus","Disruption of the sacro-iliac joint","Dislocation of the hip"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhat is described above is that of a \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior hip dislocation\u003C/strong\u003E. This type of dislocation often occurs when a person\u0027s knee hits the car dashboard in a motor-vehicle collision. This force drives the femoral head posteriorly, tearing through the weakest points of the joint capsule, being the inferior and posterior aspects. This results in the limb becoming shortened and adducted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAssociated posterior hip dislocation injuries include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPosterior wall acetabular fracture\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnterior femoral head fracture\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFemoral head osteonecrosis (5-40%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESciatic nerve injury (10-20%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERecurrent dislocations (\u0026lt;2%)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeck of femur fractures (NOFs) \u003C/strong\u003Eare commonly associated with osteoporosis in the elderly population and result from low energy falls. In the younger population they tend to occur as a result of high energy accidents such as the one mentioned in the stem. What makes this diagnosis less like is that NOF\u0027s manifest clinically with a shortened and externally rotated lower limb, due to the distal fragment of the bone being pulled upwards and rotated laterally by the external rotator muscles of the hip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetabular fractures \u003C/strong\u003Eusually result from high energy injuries such as motor-vehicle accidents or fall from a significant height. More often than not, there are other serious injuries (eg pelvic fractures) in addition to the acetabular fracture, with some 50% of these patients having chest or abdominal injuries. Once again, in elderly individuals or those with osteoporosis, it can result from low energy falls. Associated injuries are incredibly common with this fracture type (hip dislocations, NOFs, etc.) and require specialist input for definitive management due to their complex nature. On the basis that this patient does not appear to have any other injuries, an acetabular fracture is a less likely explanation for his current problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIsolated \u003Cstrong\u003Epubic rami fractures\u003C/strong\u003E are often as a result of trauma and would not result in the lower limb features described in the stem. These types of fractures are frequently treated conservatively following expert input.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisruption of the sacro-iliac joint \u003C/strong\u003Emay result from high energy trauma and usually from a lateral compression force. Definitive diagnose often requires CT scan and may require open reduction with anterior and posterior pelvic ring fixation as required. This type of injury would not result in the lower limb features described in the stem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Posterior hip dislocation is the most common type of hip dislocation and occurs in approximately 90% of cases","The affected limb presents in slight flexion, adduction and internally rotated"],"references":["Mehta S, Routt ML Jr. Irreducible fracture-dislocations of the femoral head without posterior wall acetabular fractures. J Orthop Trauma. 2008 Nov-Dec;22(10):686-92. doi: 10.1097/BOT.0b013e31818e2a86. PMID: 18978543. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18978543/","Stannard JP, Harris HW, Volgas DA, Alonso JE. Functional outcome of patients with femoral head fractures associated with hip dislocations. Clin Orthop Relat Res. 2000 Aug;(377):44-56. doi: 10.1097/00003086-200008000-00008. PMID: 10943184. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10943184/","Dawson-Amoah K, Raszewski J, Duplantier N, Waddell BS. Dislocation of the Hip: A Review of Types, Causes, and Treatment. Ochsner J. 2018 Fall;18(3):242-252. doi: 10.31486/toj.17.0079. PMID: 30275789; PMCID: PMC6162140. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30275789/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65870"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11742"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65870"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T17:05:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T17:07:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4355"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80579"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags